A '''chief content officer''' ('''CCO''') is a corporate executive responsible for the digital media creation and multi-channel publication of the organization's content (text, video, audio, animation, etc.).

The CCO is usually an [[executive (management)|executive]] role or [[senior vice president]] position, typically reporting to the [[chief executive officer]] or the [[president (corporate title)|president]] of the organization.

In a [[broadcasting]] [[organisation]], the CCO is generally the highest ranking creative member of the organization. However, the chief content officer position is also common in many other industries, ranging from insurance to video production based on a [[LinkedIn]] study.<ref>{{cite web|author=Robert|title=Chief Content Officers|url=http://www.pdxseo.net/chief-content-officers-portland-media-marketing-masters/|publisher=PDX SEO|accessdate=6 May 2016}}</ref>

==Responsibilities==
Like all other chief officers, the chief content officer is responsible for supervision, coordination, planning and operation in his or her own field of responsibility.<ref name="ContentMarketingInstitute">{{cite web |url=http://contentmarketinginstitute.com/2011/05/chief-content-officer-job-description-sample-example-tempate/ |title=The Job Description of Chief Executive Officer, Sample Template |work=contentmarketinginstitute.com |accessdate=2015-07-01 }}</ref> The CCO may also lead a company's [[Brand|branding]] and [[marketing]] efforts (as it relates to content), if these areas are not overseen by a [[chief marketing officer]]. In certain businesses which are involved in media creation such as [[Netflix]], a CCO is responsible for developing original [[Television program|programming]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Richardson|first1=Ben|title=The Rise Of The Chief Content Officer|url=http://www.acuitytraining.co.uk/news-tips/rise-chief-content-officer/|website=Acuity Training|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>

